b'' b"extract from the color readme file for anthony's icon library." b'for network discussion...' b'' b'color coordination...' b'' b"i tried to start a discussion in `comp.windows.x' at the start of the" b"year about some sort of `standard color table' that icons should follow" b'(say to colors including colors for a small grey scale). but no' b'one responded at all.' b'' b'the problem is that if the colors for icons are just used willy-nilly' b'you will soon find that the workstations color table, devotes itself' b"solely the window manager, icons and other `adminstrative tasks' instead" b'of applications that actually require the colors for proper working.' b"``color needful applications'' such as picture and graphic displayers," b'animation, real time video, raytracers, etc... b'' b'the following is a suggested color table for icons, and general use.' b'icons, window managers, and general applications, should follow this' b"table or something like it, unless the application is ``color needful''." b'' b'* for each primary color (red,green,blue) three colors' b'eg: values and b'this results in colors representing most of the' b'standard colors for use in icons.' b'' b'* two extra shades of grey' b'eg: vales (black) and (white,red,...)' b'' b'* other colors probably of some primary color to provide shading' b'a and 3-d look to buttons and titlebars in the window manager.' b'' b'this table represents colors and represents a large range of' b"posibilities for the above ``administrative services'' of the" b'workstation.' b'' b'' b'------------------------------------------------------------------------------' b'a gods idea of amusement is a snakes ladders game, with greased rungs.' b'- terry pratchett "wyrd sisters"' b'------------------------------------------------------------------------------' 